      "content": "A nitrogen imbalance can be a common cause of yellowing leaves. To fix it, you can test your soil pH and nitrogen levels using a DIY kit or sending a sample to a lab. If the pH is too low (acidic) or too high (alkaline), or the nitrogen levels are low, you can adjust the soil accordingly. For tomatoes, a more neutral to slightly acidic pH (6.0-6.8) and moderate nitrogen levels (around 10-20 ppm) are ideal. You may need to add organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure to raise the pH and improve soil structure.",
